Adjust racks to middle and top positions and preheat oven to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil.

Reserve half the @mozzarella cheese{1/4%cup} in a #small bowl (you'll use the rest in the next step).

In a #large bowl, soak @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}(half) with 2 tbsp water; let sit until absorbed.

Add @ground beef{10%ounce}, half the @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon}(half), @salt{3/4%tsp}, and @pepper{} to #bowl with panade.

Form into four 3-inch-wide rounds; divide remaining @mozzarella cheese{1/4%cup} between the centers of each. Gently fold meat around cheese, shaping and sealing to create cheese-stuffed meatballs.

Lightly oil a #baking sheet{}. Spread meatballs out across sheet.

Bake on middle rack until cooked through, ~{20-22%minutes}. (It's OK if some cheese oozes out!) Remove sheet from oven.

Heat broiler to high.

Once water is boiling, add @rigatoni pasta{6%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain and set aside.

While pasta cooks, place @butter{1%tbsp} in a second #small microwave-safe bowl{}; microwave until melted, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in remaining panko, 1/4 tsp Tuscan Heat Spice, @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{}.

Once meatballs and pasta are done, heat a large, preferably ovenproof, #pan over medium-high heat. Stir in @marinara{14%ounce}, remaining Tuscan Heat Spice, 1/2 cup reserved pasta cooking water, @sugar{1%tsp}, and @salt{1/2%tsp}. Bring to a simmer and cook until slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Remove from heat; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Season generously with salt and pepper.

Stir drained rigatoni and meatballs into pan with sauce. If needed, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time until everything is thoroughly coated in sauce. Top pasta with @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, reserved mozzarella, and panko mixture.

Broil until panko is golden brown and cheese melts, ~{1-2%minutes}. Let cool slightly, then serve.

> If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer mixture now to a 9-by-13-inch #baking dish{}.

> Watch carefully while broiling to avoid burning.